text=>>comment%3c%3c%0aSummary:some excellent tips on creativity from the man who studied Flow%0aParent:(Consulting.)ChangeManagement%0aIncludeMe:[[Consulting.ChangeManagement]]%0aCategories:[[!Articles]]%0aTags: creativity, Csikszentmihalyi%0a(:tags-hide creativity, Csikszentmihalyi :)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a!! Csikszentmihalyi on Creativity%0a%0aFrom "Creativity" by Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi%0a%0a"How can interest and curiosity be cultivated, assuming that you feel%0athe desire to do so? Some specific advice may help.%0a%0a'''TRY TO BE SURPRISED BY SOMETHING EVERY DAY.''' Stop to look at the%0aunusual car parked at the curb, taste the new item on the cafeteria%0amenu, actually listen to your colleague at the office...How is this%0adifferent from other similar cars, dishes, or conversations? What is%0aits essence?...Experience this one thing for what it is, not what you%0athink it is. Be open to what the world is telling you. Life is nothing%0amore than a stream of experiences -- the more widely and deeply you%0aswim in it, the richer your life will be.%0a%0a'''TRY TO SURPRISE ONE PERSON EVERY DAY.''' Instead of being your%0apredictable self, say something unexpected, express an opinion that%0ayou have not dared to reveal, ask a question you wouldn't ordinarily%0aask. Or break the routine of your activities: Invite a person to go%0awith you to a show, a restaurant or a museum you never visited%0abefore. Experiment with your appearance. Comfortable routines are%0agreat when they save energy for doing what you really care about; but%0aif you are still searching, they restrict and limit the future.%0a%0a'''WRITE DOWN EVERY DAY WHAT SURPRISED YOU AND HOW YOU SURPRISED OTHERS.'''  %0aOne of the surest ways to enrich life is to make%0aexperiences less fleeting, so that the most memorable, interesting,%0aand important events are not lost forever a few hours after they%0aoccurred. Writing them down so that you can relive them in%0arecollection is one way to keep them from disappearing. And after a%0afew weeks, you may begin to see a pattern of interest emerging in the%0anotes, one that may indicate some domain that would repay exploring in%0adepth.%0a%0a'''WHEN SOMETHING STRIKES A SPARK OF INTEREST, FOLLOW IT.''' Usually,%0awhen something captures our attention -- an idea, a song, a flower --%0athe impression is brief. We are too busy to explore further...Or we%0afeel that it is none of our business...Of course, that's nonsense. The%0aworld IS our business, and we can't know which part of it is%0abestsuited to our selves, to our potentialities, unless we make a%0aserious effort to learn about as many aspects of it as possible.%0a%0aIf you take the time to reflect on how best to implement these four%0asuggestions, and then actuallly start putting them into effect, you%0ashould feel a stirring of possibilities under the accustomed surface%0aof daily experience. It is the gathering of creative energy, the%0arebirth of curiosity that has been atrophied since childhood.%0a%0a----%0a%0a[[http://www.google.com/search?q=Csikszentmihalyi|Google Search on Csikszentmihalyi]] %0a
